"Nyberg P., Bergstrand E., Degerman E., Enderlein O.","Recruitment of pelagic fish in an unstable climate: Studies in Sweden's four largest lakes",2001,"Ambio","30","8",,"559","564",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035544435&partnerID=40&md5=129c89ee26b7d91c83631ff9c3b6ac9d","Institute of Freshwater Research, National Fishery Board, Pappersbruksallén 22, SE-702 15 Örebro, Sweden","Nyberg, P., Institute of Freshwater Research, National Fishery Board, Pappersbruksallén 22, SE-702 15 Örebro, Sweden; Bergstrand, E., Institute of Freshwater Research, National Fishery Board, Pappersbruksallén 22, SE-702 15 Örebro, Sweden; Degerman, E., Institute of Freshwater Research, National Fishery Board, Pappersbruksallén 22, SE-702 15 Örebro, Sweden; Enderlein, O., Institute of Freshwater Research, National Fishery Board, Pappersbruksallén 22, SE-702 15 Örebro, Sweden","Pelagic fish population biology was studied in the large Swedish lakes Vänern, Vättern, Mälaren and Hjälmaren. It is crucial for fish fry in temperate regions to hatch early in the growth season to survive, and achieve large size before winter, and it is suggested that the key factors are to match the spring development of phyto- and zoo-plankton, but to avoid predation. This is more easily accomplished by the studied spring spawners smelt (Osmerus eperlanus) and pike-perch (Stizostedion lucioperca) than autumn spawners, such as vendace (Coregonus albula). It is shown that hatching of vendace fry shortly after ice-break-up is beneficial for year-class strength. In oligotrophic large lakes with few predatory species a rapid increase in water temperature after icebreak is also promoting recruitment, whereas this is not the case in eutrophic lakes where predation pressure from other species may become too high. The results indicate that autumn spawners will have difficulties in adapting to global warming and it is also suggested that the life history can explain the large variations observed in year-class strength between years.",,"lake; pelagic fish; recruitment; spawning; Sweden; Albula; Coregonus albula; Lucioperca; Osmerus eperlanus; Stizostedion lucioperca; fresh water; animal; article; climate; ecosystem; environmental monitoring; feeding behavior; fish; methodology; physiology; population dynamics; reproduction; season; Sweden; Animals; Climate; Ecosystem; Environmental Monitoring; Feeding Behavior; Fishes; Fresh Water; Population Dynamics; Reproduction; Seasons; Sweden",,,,,,"Degerman, E., Hammar, J., Nyberg, P., Svärdson, G., Human impact on the fish diversity in the four largest lakes of Sweden (2001) Ambio, 30, pp. 522-528; Karjalainen, J., Survival, growth and feeding of vendace, Coregonus albula (L.), larvae in net enclosures (1991) J. Fish Biol., 38, pp. 905-919; Koho, J., Karjalainen, J., Viljanen, M., Effects of temperature, food density and time of hatching on growth, survival and feeding of vendace (Coregonus albula (L.)) larvae (1991) Aqua Fenn., 21, pp. 63-73; Huusko, A., Sutela, T., Fish predation on vendace (Coregonus albula L.) larvae in Lake Lentua, northern Finland (1992) Pol. Arch. Hydrobiol., 39, pp. 381-391. , Biology and management of coregonid Fishes. Todd, T.N. and Luczynski, M. (eds); Sandlund, O.T., Differences in the ecology of two vendace populations separated in 1895 (1992) Nord. J. Freshw. Res., 67, pp. 52-60; Naesje, T.F., Jonsson, B., Impacted stress: A causal agent of reduced whitefish (Coregonus lavaretus) egg incubation time (1988) Can. J. Fish. Aquat. Sci., 45, pp. 27-31; Nilsson, N.-A., Food and habitat of the fish community of the offshore region of Lake Vänern, Sweden (1979) Rep. Inst. Freshw. Res., 50, pp. 133-167; Enderlein, O., Interspecific food competition between the three pelagic zooplanktonfeeders, cisco (Coregonus albula (L.)), smelt (Osmerus eperlanus (L.)) and herring (Clupea harengus (L.)) in the Norrbotten part of the Bothnian Bay (1981) Rep. Inst. Freshw. Res., Drottningholm, 59, pp. 15-20; Enderlei